    section .data
        hw db &quot;Hello, world.&quot;,10
    
    section .text
        global hello
    
    hello:
        mov rax, 1
        mov rdi, 1
        mov rsi, text
        mov rdx, 14
        syscall
        ret

I compiled all of them, compiling the third in two steps since I had to separately call the compiler and the linker. I used `nasm` (version 2.13.02) to compile the Assembly file. I compiled the C codes with `gcc (GCC) 7.3.1 20180303 (Red Hat 7.3.1-5)`. Then I checked the sizes of the compiled binaries.

What I found was that in each case, the size was just the same - about 8.1 KiB. I had assumed that the sized of the three files would have been different, but in hindsight it seems that the sizes are the same because whether I ask for it or not, GCC always links the Standard Library to my code. So I ran one more test.

I wrote this code:

    #include &lt;math.h&gt;
    #include &lt;stdio.h&gt;
    
    int main()
    {
      printf(&quot;The square root of 16 is %lf\n&quot;, sqrt(16));
    
